      <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
       Asia’s strategic gatekeeper
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: India’s foreign policy-based strategic autonomy complicates US-China competition.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
            As US-China tensions rise, both the Trump and Biden administrations saw <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jun-25-analysis-h1-6-india-as-a-key-partner" target="_blank">India as a key partner</a> against China. The US’s concerns over economic security and Taiwan have boosted India's strategic role. India’s involvement in US-led initiatives, such as the Quad, has increased, especially since the 2020 border clashes with China.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        India has also been frustrated with China for interfering with subcontinental issues. China has backed Pakistan and has made a lot of projects with it. They are also courting Bangladesh amid a diplomatic fallout. It continues to resist Chinese military assertiveness, particularly on the border. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        However, India's commitment to the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jun-25-analysis-h1-7-strategic-autonomy" target="_blank">strategic autonomy</a> element of its foreign policy program can complicate the relationship. India relies on Chinese supply chains, especially in the solar and pharmaceutical sectors. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        They have shared Ideology, including anti-Western sentiments, multipolarity, and participation in institutions like BRICS and the AIIB. India circumvents formal alliances. It keeps ties with Russia and Iran. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        However, Modi and Trump share a personal bond and similar views on nationalism. This provides the US a possibility to deepen ties if it acknowledges New Delhi’s balancing measures and nuanced approach to global power dynamics. 
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
