 Why does Djibouti have so many military bases? 
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/pla-djibouti-military-base-opening-ceremony.jpg" alt="Chinese People’s Liberation Army personnel attending the opening ceremony of China’s military base in Djibouti" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>Chinese People’s Liberation Army personnel attending the opening ceremony of China’s military base in Djibouti. Credits: STR/AFP via Getty Images.</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
       Djibouti might be small, but it plays a significant role in geopolitics. Its strategic position near the Bab el-Mandeb Strait, a strategic gateway between the Red Sea and the Gulf of Aden, acts as a vital checkpoint for global trade. It's close to Yemen, Somalia, and other unstable areas, making it ideal for anti-terrorism, anti-piracy, and military monitoring.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Djibouti employs "<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jun-25-foundations-h1-14-small-state-diplomacy" target="_blank">small state diplomacy</a>" to maximize economic and security benefits by <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-jun-25-foundations-h1-15-leasing-its-territory" target="_blank">leasing its territory</a> for foreign military use. Djibouti has at least eight foreign military bases from countries like the US, China, Japan, France, and Saudi Arabia. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        These foreign bases generate significant revenue to boost the economy. The country receives $70M in annual rent from these bases. Yet, a select few can benefit from the revenue, which goes to a small group of elites. Poverty and unemployment are major problems in Djibouti. 
        </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
      Despite the social issues, Djibouti plays a key role in regional and global security. Especially with the rising tensions in the Red Sea, the resurgence of piracy, and amplified competition among major powers. 
        </p>
        </mj-text>
